1. Basics of Multitasking & Thread Fundamentals
        

1) What is multitasking in Java?
-->Multitasking is the process of executing multiple tasks simultaneously within a system. In Java, multitasking helps improve CPU
    utilization and application performance. It can be achieved using processes or threads.
        
        Multitasking is the process of executing multiple tasks simultaneously in a system.
        
        In Java, multitasking allows a program to perform more than one activity at the same time, which improves:
        
        CPU utilization
        Performance
        Responsiveness of applications
        Example:
        Listening to music while downloading files
        A web server handling multiple users at the same time
        
        Java supports two types of multitasking:
        
        Process-based multitasking
        Thread-based multitasking


2) What is the difference between process-based and thread-based multitasking?
-->
| Feature           | Process-Based Multitasking                        | Thread-Based Multitasking            |
| ----------------- | ------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------ |
| Unit of execution | Process                                           | Thread                               |
| Memory            | Separate memory for each process                  | Shared memory within same process    |
| Communication     | Difficult and slower                              | Easy and faster                      |
| Creation cost     | High                                              | Low                                  |
| Context switching | Heavy                                             | Lightweight                          |
| Failure impact    | One process failure usually doesn’t affect others | One thread may affect entire process |
| Example           | Opening Chrome + VS Code                          | Multiple tabs/tasks inside browser   |
    Real-Time Example
    Process = Entire WhatsApp application
    Thread = Sending messages, receiving messages, notifications simultaneously


3) What is a thread in Java?
-->A thread is the smallest unit of execution inside a process.
        
        It is also called:
        
        Lightweight process
        Independent path of execution
        
        Threads allow multiple tasks to run concurrently within a single program.
        
        Example:
            In a video player:
                One thread plays video
                Another thread plays audio
                Another thread loads subtitles



4) What is multithreading, and why is it needed & advantages of multithreading?
-->Multithreading
        
        Multithreading is the process of executing multiple threads simultaneously within a single program.
        
        Java provides built-in support for multithreading.
        
        Why is Multithreading Needed?
        
        Without multithreading:
        
        Programs become slow
        UI freezes
        CPU resources are wasted
        
        With multithreading:
        
        Multiple tasks run concurrently
        Applications become faster and more responsive
        Advantages of Multithreading
        1. Better CPU Utilization
        
        CPU remains busy by executing multiple tasks.
        
        2. Faster Execution
        
        Multiple tasks execute simultaneously.
        
        3. Responsive Applications
        
        UI remains active even during heavy operations.
        
        Example:
        
        While downloading a file, you can still click buttons.
        
        4. Resource Sharing
        
        Threads share the same memory area.
        
        5. Economical
        
        Creating threads is cheaper than creating processes.
        
        6. Real-Time Processing
        
        Useful in:
            Gaming
            Web servers
            Banking systems
            Chat applications
5) What is the main thread in Java & how is the main thread created automatically by the JVM?
-->Main Thread  
        The main thread is the first thread created automatically by the JVM when a Java program starts.
        
        Every Java program starts execution from:
        
        public static void main(String[] args)
                This main() method runs inside the main thread.
                How JVM Creates Main Thread Automatically
                
        When JVM starts execution:    
                JVM loads the class
                JVM creates the main thread automatically
                Main thread executes the main() method
        Example
        class Demo {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
                System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName());
            }
        }
        Output:
            main  
        Here:
            Thread.currentThread()
            returns the currently executing thread.



6) What happens if the main thread terminates before child threads?
-->If the main thread terminates:  
        Child threads continue execution independently
        JVM terminates only when all non-daemon threads finish execution
        Example
        class MyThread extends Thread {
            public void run() {
                for(int i=1; i<=5; i++) {
                    System.out.println(i);
                }
            }
        }
        
        class Demo {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
                MyThread t = new MyThread();
                t.start();
        
                System.out.println("Main thread ended");
            }
        }
        Possible Output
        Main thread ended
        1
        2
        3
        4
        5
        
        Even after main thread ends, child thread continues.




7) How many ways can you create a thread in Java?
-->There are mainly 2 ways:        
        1. Extending Thread Class
                class MyThread extends Thread {
                    public void run() {
                        System.out.println("Thread is running");
                    }
                }
                class Demo {
                    public static void main(String[] args) {
                        MyThread t = new MyThread();
                        t.start();
                    }
                }


        2. Implementing Runnable Interface
                class MyRunnable implements Runnable {
                    public void run() {
                        System.out.println("Thread is running");
                    }
                }
                class Demo {
                    public static void main(String[] args) {
                        MyRunnable r = new MyRunnable();
                
                        Thread t = new Thread(r);
                
                        t.start();
                    }
                }


8) What is the difference between extending Thread class and implementing Runnable interface?
-->
| Feature              | Extending Thread     | Implementing Runnable         |
| -------------------- | -------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| Inheritance          | Extends Thread class | Implements Runnable interface |
| Multiple inheritance | Not possible         | Possible                      |
| Flexibility          | Less flexible        | More flexible                 |
| Resource sharing     | Difficult            | Easier                        |
| Recommended          | Less preferred       | Most preferred                |
| Method to override   | `run()`              | `run()`                       |
